Previous Next 

Kathleen Sebelius: “The Product is There, The Product is Good” [Videos] 
Secretary Kathleen Sebelius talks to Dr. Sanjay Gupta.
“The interest is there.” – Secretary Kathleen Sebelius
IN THE conversation, Secretary Kathleen Sebelius she said there had been 1,100,000 calls, with “500,000 plus” accounts of people who are shopping for coverage, with monthly figures promised.  How well is it working?  
“Thousands of people have signed up… It is not where we need it to be … The good news is we have a product, we have a market, we have competitive plans, affordable prices, and no one will ever be locked out of the insurance market with a pre-existing condition and that’s good news…” – Secretary Kathleen Sebelius
In what is a stunning admission, Secretary Kathleen Sebelius said that President Obama didn’t know about the website problems before ACA launched on October 1. 
Secretary Kathleen Sebelius didn’t consider resigning, but simply doing the job she was charged to do, which she sees as the most important work of her life.  Dr. Sanjay Gupta pressed her on this topic, but resigning wasn’t something she wanted to discuss, for obvious reasons.
“Accelerating the fixes” is the first order of business.  “This will be fixed as quickly as possible,” Secretary Sebelius said, but she couldn’t give Dr. Sanjay Gupta a specific date.
“Millions of Americans want this product,” she said, which is no doubt.
A lot of people aren’t tech savvy, with “lots of people” wanting a “live body” to talk to about signing up.  This “isn’t a website, it’s about health care and about affordable plans.”  
Whether the individual mandate will be delayed is “not really the question right now,” according to Sebelius.  “You need everybody to come into the pool… we need people to sign up.”
Secretary Sebelius said at the end of the interview that she is looking to the enrollment figures at the end of March 2014, when open enrollment ends.  It sounds like that’s when we’ll know the full numbers and success of the launch of ACA.  Right as the 2014 midterms are gearing up.
I’m not sure anything Kathleen Sebelius says will change the dynamic right now, but it’s an interview she had to do, with more Administration officials needed to continue making the case.  If people don’t have confidence not enough will sign up, which will hamper the effectiveness of ACA.  
Those of us who have insurance aren’t impacted by ACA’s open enrollment period, but there are millions of uninsured who absolutely do need health care who are depending on the Obama administration delivering.  
Concerns will remain until stories from uninsured signing up and the numbers of those who getting insurance start shifting and actual numbers of those successfully enrolling are offered and confirmed.  




By Taylor Marsh|October 23rd, 2013|13 Comments 
